This is good, and it has aged well. It's sad, it's creepy, it's believable. My only problem with it is the nagging question (which keeps coming up in discussion) of how long she has been 3 years old. No, that's a serious question. It matters. You don't have to tell the reader, and I would recommend against doing so, but the Foundation does know, and it should be noted. If she has been observed to not age, there absolutely 0.00% chance that that wouldn't have been noted in the notes. If this has not happened, it would be assumed that she does age, and that means that saying  without a date stamp is about as useless as talking about the left side of a sphere.

In short, if she doesn't age, you damn well better put in a footnote because that's a really noteworthy anomaly. That would be anomalous enough to contain even without other effects.

If she does age (or if we haven't noticed yet, since she's only been in containment for ██ months) then it should say that she  Or 12-17-████, or whatever.

It matters because it would matter to the researchers for whom this is written. They have to plan for long-term containment. It will matter to them when she hits puberty, when she turns 21. It will matter how long she's been in containment and how she has developed and whether and how her effects have changed.

If this is meant to be a snapshot of her right after recovery, fine  without saying where the front is or where you are.







